Competition between public and private firms is very common.1 An interesting issue is whether or not public firms engage in innovation more aggressively than private firms. This question becomes even more interesting in the case of externalities. A typical example is the attempt to fight against severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS). On March 17, 2003, immediately after the outbreak of SARS in China, World Heath Organization (WHO) called upon 11 laboratories in 9 countries to join a collaborative research project on SARS diagnosis.2 Since then, public institutes of many countries spent a broad effort to develop vaccines and drugs against the SARS virus. Private firms, not certain whether the market will be long lasting, first hesitated to invest in SARS research.3 Later on, attracted by government funding and expectation of short-run profit, they switched some of their focus to the infectious disease.4
